│ stop({"edit_points": [[5526, 5527, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyCFG.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\n\nThe crash occurs when `CleanupReturnInst::getCleanupPad()` tries to cast its     │
│ first operand to a `CleanupPadInst`, but the operand is actually a `PoisonValue` (token poison). This happens because during CFG simplification, some cleanuppad instructions are replaced with poison values  │
│ when their blocks are being deleted, but the corresponding cleanupret instructions still reference these poison values.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\n\nThe debug log shows that several blocks are being      │
│ removed as dead code:\n- `panic1` (invoke block)\n- `funclet_bb14` (cleanuppad block) \n- `unreachable` (unreachable block)\n\nAfter these removals, there's a cleanupret instruction in `bb13` that           │
│ references `%cleanuppad`, but this cleanuppad was in the now-deleted `funclet_bb14` block. The cleanuppad gets replaced with poison, but the cleanupret still exists and tries to access it.\n\n3. Root Cause  │
│ Analysis:\n\nLooking at the `simplifyCleanupReturn` function in `SimplifyCFG.cpp`, there's already a check for `UndefValue` operands on line 5526, with a comment explaining that \"It is possible to          │
│ transiantly have an undef cleanuppad operand because we have deleted some, but not all, dead blocks.\" However, the code doesn't check for `PoisonValue` operands, which can also occur during dead block      │
│ elimination.\n\nIn the debugger, we confirmed that the problematic `CleanupReturnInst` has a `token poison` operand instead of a valid `CleanupPadInst`. The existing check only handles `UndefValue` but not  │
│ `PoisonValue`, causing the cast assertion to fail.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n\nThe fix is to extend the existing check in `simplifyCleanupReturn` to also handle `PoisonValue` operands, similar to how   │
│ it already handles `UndefValue`. This should be done at line 5526 in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SimplifyCFG.cpp`.\n\n5. Conclusion:\n\nBy adding a check for `PoisonValue` alongside the existing `UndefValue` │
│ check, we prevent the invalid cast that causes the assertion failure. This allows the pass to safely skip processing cleanupret instructions that reference dead cleanuppad instructions, which will           │
│ eventually be cleaned up by dead block elimination."})                                                                                                                                                         │
